00:03:04.935 --> 00:03:09.102
So with that said, The Lanterman
Developmental Disabilities

00:03:12.605 --> 00:03:17.025
Services Act, as you
know was passed in 1969.

00:03:17.025 --> 00:03:20.106
And it just celebrated
its 50th anniversary.

00:03:20.106 --> 00:03:22.666
But the biggest thing about
this Lanterman Entitlement Act

00:03:22.666 --> 00:03:25.586
is that it's the only Entitlement Act

00:03:25.586 --> 00:03:27.257
of all of the 50 states.

00:03:27.257 --> 00:03:30.362
So California has the only
entitlement for services

00:03:30.362 --> 00:03:33.945
for people with
developmental disabilities.

00:03:42.145 --> 00:03:45.734
We have a mission statement,
we have a vision statement.

00:03:45.734 --> 00:03:48.525
The mission statement
is to ensure that people

00:03:48.525 --> 00:03:50.911
with developmental
disabilities have the ability

00:03:50.911 --> 00:03:53.828
to live lives just as you and I do.

00:03:55.617 --> 00:03:58.319
Our mission statement
is that and our vision

00:03:58.319 --> 00:04:00.252
building partnerships
and supporting choices

00:04:00.252 --> 00:04:03.847
is really about a system
of partnering with folks

00:04:03.847 --> 00:04:07.899
so that our system works together as one.

00:04:07.899 --> 00:04:12.066
It's a system structure
for people to work together

00:04:13.201 --> 00:04:16.715
and agencies to work together
and everybody to work together

00:04:16.715 --> 00:04:18.902
to make services support
available for people

00:04:18.902 --> 00:04:20.799
with developmental disabilities.

00:04:20.799 --> 00:04:23.882
When we look at our system structure,

00:04:24.929 --> 00:04:25.762
you'll notice that it starts

00:04:25.762 --> 00:04:27.546
with the governor's office of course.

00:04:27.546 --> 00:04:29.314
We have the health and
human services agency

00:04:29.314 --> 00:04:31.083
which the departmental
and developmental services

00:04:31.083 --> 00:04:35.021
is apart of and then we have
the state developmental centers

00:04:35.021 --> 00:04:37.624
as well as one state
operated community facility.

00:04:37.624 --> 00:04:40.822
Which is run by the state
and has state employees

00:04:40.822 --> 00:04:44.324
and then we contract
with 21 regional centers.

00:04:44.324 --> 00:04:46.763
Often times people call the department

00:04:46.763 --> 00:04:50.073
and ask us to, have an issue
with the regional center

00:04:50.073 --> 00:04:52.165
and they want department
of developmental services

00:04:52.165 --> 00:04:54.306
to address it immediately.

00:04:54.306 --> 00:04:57.009
And we often times, unless
it has something to do with

00:04:57.009 --> 00:04:59.155
a violation of law regulation.

00:04:59.155 --> 00:05:01.759
We have to refer them back
to the regional center

00:05:01.759 --> 00:05:03.923
because the regional centers are all

00:05:03.923 --> 00:05:05.506
and a lot of people are surprised by this.

00:05:05.506 --> 00:05:06.433
The regional centers are all

00:05:06.433 --> 00:05:08.396
private non-profit organizations

00:05:08.396 --> 00:05:10.391
and they answer to a board of directors.

00:05:10.391 --> 00:05:13.543
Other than violations
of law and regulation

00:05:13.543 --> 00:05:16.066
everything else, we can address things

00:05:16.066 --> 00:05:17.938
that have to do with a
violation of law and regulation

00:05:17.938 --> 00:05:19.604
but everything else has to go through

00:05:19.604 --> 00:05:22.814
their regional center
director and their board.

00:05:22.814 --> 00:05:24.184
So one of the big examples

00:05:24.184 --> 00:05:26.515
that we get is often times people,

00:05:26.515 --> 00:05:28.416
vendors might get vendored to serve

00:05:28.416 --> 00:05:31.658
like a residential provider
might get vendored to serve six

00:05:31.658 --> 00:05:33.779
or get license to serve six people.

00:05:33.779 --> 00:05:36.525
And the regional center tells
them, well vendor you forfour

00:05:36.525 --> 00:05:38.052
and they'll call the department and say,

00:05:38.052 --> 00:05:40.111
I got license for six people.

00:05:40.111 --> 00:05:41.579
I want six people in my home.

00:05:41.579 --> 00:05:43.806
The regional centers says
they'll only give me four.

00:05:43.806 --> 00:05:45.665
That is not something that the department

00:05:45.665 --> 00:05:47.140
can do something about.

00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:49.392
That is a regional center
and their board of directors

00:05:49.392 --> 00:05:51.973
decision to serve people in that manner.

00:05:51.973 --> 00:05:53.764
And that's how regional
centers were set up

00:05:53.764 --> 00:05:57.200
to do what their local
community feels is the most

00:05:57.200 --> 00:05:58.534
appropriate way to serve folks.

00:05:58.534 --> 00:06:01.586
So that's not a violation
of law and regulation

00:06:01.586 --> 00:06:03.488
and when we get calls
about that we refer them

00:06:03.488 --> 00:06:04.624
back to the regional center

00:06:04.624 --> 00:06:07.795
because that's the way our system works.

00:06:07.795 --> 00:06:09.727
The regional centers have case managers

00:06:09.727 --> 00:06:11.440
that help coordinate services

00:06:11.440 --> 00:06:13.713
and they vendor service providers

00:06:13.713 --> 00:06:15.894
who actually provide direct services

00:06:15.894 --> 00:06:18.507
and supports to our consumers.

00:06:18.507 --> 00:06:21.795
And all of that is done through a IPP

00:06:21.795 --> 00:06:25.045
and a person centered planning process.

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:32.004
So as I said they contract
with these 21 regional centers,

00:06:32.004 --> 00:06:34.207
the 21 regional centers
are private non profit.

00:06:34.207 --> 00:06:35.455
They are 21 regional centers

00:06:35.455 --> 00:06:38.705
to cover all 56 counties of California.

00:06:40.095 --> 00:06:43.741
Regional centers work with
approximately 45,000 vendors

00:06:43.741 --> 00:06:46.214
who provide those direct services

00:06:46.214 --> 00:06:49.797
and we work with a system of
partners, other organizations,

00:06:49.797 --> 00:06:52.021
stakeholder groups, individuals, families

00:06:52.021 --> 00:06:55.771
to implement the vision
of The Lanterman Act.

00:06:59.046 --> 00:07:02.981
So what's been going
on the last few years?

00:07:02.981 --> 00:07:04.868
More than a few years I guess.

00:07:04.868 --> 00:07:08.160
From 2002-2016, you can see the growth

00:07:08.160 --> 00:07:10.410
in our consumer population.

00:07:11.907 --> 00:07:16.074
As of December of 2016,
we're serving 304,000 people.

00:07:21.259 --> 00:07:23.263
When you look at the
regional center population,

00:07:23.263 --> 00:07:24.737
from the smallest regional center,

00:07:24.737 --> 00:07:26.290
Redwood Coast Regional Center,

00:07:26.290 --> 00:07:28.645
up at the northern tip of California

00:07:28.645 --> 00:07:30.715
verses Inland Regional
Center in the San Bernadine.

00:07:30.715 --> 00:07:33.677
You see Redwood Coast serving 3600 folks

00:07:33.677 --> 00:07:36.911
and Inland Regional Center 31,300 folks

00:07:36.911 --> 00:07:41.078
with the average regional
center serving 14,000 folks.

00:07:42.912 --> 00:07:47.079
The way this consumer population
is growing essentially

00:07:48.494 --> 00:07:52.494
we could start a new
regional center every year.

00:07:56.892 --> 00:07:59.142
Consumer population by age.

00:08:01.851 --> 00:08:04.690
As we gather this type of
information at the department,

00:08:04.690 --> 00:08:07.362
this is one of the areas
where we look at trends

00:08:07.362 --> 00:08:10.288
to see what's going on and
see what kind of resources

00:08:10.288 --> 00:08:12.379
need to be developed and
what kind of legislation

00:08:12.379 --> 00:08:16.225
might need to be addressed to
address some of the trends.

00:08:16.225 --> 00:08:18.430
One of the things you'll notice here

00:08:18.430 --> 00:08:22.983
is that our elderly seniors
are beginning to grow

00:08:22.983 --> 00:08:24.350
which tells us that our folks

00:08:24.350 --> 00:08:27.163
are starting to live a lot longer.

00:08:27.163 --> 00:08:29.016
One of the things that we've
done to address this is

00:08:29.016 --> 00:08:31.324
we've worked with Community Care Licensing

00:08:31.324 --> 00:08:34.539
and you may have notice this already

00:08:34.539 --> 00:08:37.152
but a lot of the Community
Care Licensing folks

00:08:37.152 --> 00:08:39.618
are now starting to allow
people to age in place.

00:08:39.618 --> 00:08:43.202
So folks that are in adult
residential facilities

00:08:43.202 --> 00:08:44.963
can stay in adult residential facilities.

00:08:44.963 --> 00:08:48.727
They don't have to simply
move because they turn 60.

00:08:48.727 --> 00:08:50.433
Usually the adult residential facilities

00:08:50.433 --> 00:08:53.393
limit is up to 59 years of age.

00:08:53.393 --> 00:08:55.245
But Community Care
Licensing is working with us

00:08:55.245 --> 00:08:57.858
and now for the most
part is allowing people

00:08:57.858 --> 00:08:59.443
unless there's some drastic differences

00:08:59.443 --> 00:09:01.050
between the consumer population.

00:09:01.050 --> 00:09:03.725
Will allow people to stay in
adult residential facilities

00:09:03.725 --> 00:09:05.975
for as long as they choose.

00:09:10.140 --> 00:09:13.289
Consumer population by living arrangement.

00:09:13.289 --> 00:09:16.213
As you can see developmental
center population continuing

00:09:16.213 --> 00:09:18.909
to go down, less people are living those.

00:09:18.909 --> 00:09:22.084
Of course that's because of our initiative

00:09:22.084 --> 00:09:24.541
to close all of our developmental centers.

00:09:24.541 --> 00:09:28.016
And as always have been the
case, regional centers work hard

00:09:28.016 --> 00:09:29.709
to support people and their families.

00:09:29.709 --> 00:09:33.894
So the family home, parent/guardian
still continues to grow

00:09:33.894 --> 00:09:36.813
and people continue to
live in their family home

00:09:36.813 --> 00:09:38.480
as long as possible.

00:09:47.453 --> 00:09:51.142
When we look at the consumer
population by diagnosis.

00:09:51.142 --> 00:09:55.309
Another thing that you see,
you can clearly see that autism

00:09:56.474 --> 00:09:59.307
growth continues to climb rapidly.

00:10:00.911 --> 00:10:05.120
This is not a secret and
we continue to provide work

00:10:05.120 --> 00:10:09.120
on developing resources
to address those issues.

00:10:13.388 --> 00:10:14.994
Population of developmental centers

00:10:14.994 --> 00:10:18.327
and state operated community facilities.

00:10:19.650 --> 00:10:23.519
You can see the steep
decline that started in 1994.

00:10:23.519 --> 00:10:25.843
I don't know if people
remembered the Coffel years

00:10:25.843 --> 00:10:29.488
when we were court ordered
to move over 2000 people

00:10:29.488 --> 00:10:32.733
out of developmental centers
within a five year period

00:10:32.733 --> 00:10:34.328
that accounts for the steep decline

00:10:34.328 --> 00:10:36.229
right there in the early years.

00:10:36.229 --> 00:10:39.497
But ever since that time, there
have been laws put in place

00:10:39.497 --> 00:10:42.232
and the lack of federal funding

00:10:42.232 --> 00:10:43.582
for some of our developmental centers,

00:10:43.582 --> 00:10:45.822
actually for all of our
developmental centers at this point.

00:10:45.822 --> 00:10:48.179
Which has cause us to make the initiative

00:10:48.179 --> 00:10:51.512
to close all of our development centers.

00:10:52.886 --> 00:10:55.371
And now we have less than
a thousand people living

00:10:55.371 --> 00:10:57.454
in developmental centers.

00:11:02.699 --> 00:11:05.949
And then we look at a few budget things

00:11:06.804 --> 00:11:08.641
and of course that is also driven

00:11:08.641 --> 00:11:11.505
by the fact that we are closing
our developmental centers.

00:11:11.505 --> 00:11:15.482
So there's more growth
in community services

00:11:15.482 --> 00:11:19.305
from 16/17 it was $5.8
billion to community services

00:11:19.305 --> 00:11:23.472
and proposed for 17/18 is $6.4 billion.

00:11:24.829 --> 00:11:27.530
That's an interesting stats
by itself because as she said,

00:11:27.530 --> 00:11:29.546
I've been doing this services

00:11:29.546 --> 00:11:31.800
for developmental disabilities
for almost 40 years

00:11:31.800 --> 00:11:34.200
and I remember when the budget

00:11:34.200 --> 00:11:35.816
for the whole regional center system

00:11:35.816 --> 00:11:38.067
was less than $20 million.

00:11:38.067 --> 00:11:42.234
So we're in the billions
now and we're working hard.

00:11:50.214 --> 00:11:52.083
And the reason that we're
able to be in the billions

00:11:52.083 --> 00:11:54.959
and the reason that we still
have an Entitlement Act

00:11:54.959 --> 00:11:56.842
is the fact that we are able

00:11:56.842 --> 00:11:59.209
to capture more federal dollars.

00:11:59.209 --> 00:12:02.209
It is imperative that the department

00:12:03.122 --> 00:12:05.314
and our service system
captures every federal dollars

00:12:05.314 --> 00:12:08.898
we can get in order to
maintain the entitlement

00:12:08.898 --> 00:12:11.230
provided by The Lanterman Act.

00:12:11.230 --> 00:12:14.763
As you can see, a little less than 50%

00:12:14.763 --> 00:12:18.828
of our funds are federal but as we move

00:12:18.828 --> 00:12:20.617
from the developmental centers systems

00:12:20.617 --> 00:12:22.444
moving everybody into the community.

00:12:22.444 --> 00:12:24.726
We'll have a lot more pressure still

00:12:24.726 --> 00:12:27.196
to maintain those federal dollars
and the federal government

00:12:27.196 --> 00:12:29.363
will still be looking at the community.

00:12:29.363 --> 00:12:32.823
In terms of the dollars that
are spent for federal funding.

00:12:32.823 --> 00:12:34.945
So we'll be under the same
types of pressures really

00:12:34.945 --> 00:12:36.395
as the developmental centers were.

00:12:36.395 --> 00:12:39.647
Developmental centers were
unable to maintain certification

00:12:39.647 --> 00:12:41.984
which is partly what's
led to their closure,

00:12:41.984 --> 00:12:43.832
other than the fact that
people shouldn't have to live

00:12:43.832 --> 00:12:45.621
in state institutions.

00:12:45.621 --> 00:12:47.419
But the other, the
driver of that has to do

00:12:47.419 --> 00:12:49.745
with they could not
maintain their certification

00:12:49.745 --> 00:12:51.538
which meant total general fund dollars

00:12:51.538 --> 00:12:54.014
were going into funding
the developmental centers.

00:12:54.014 --> 00:12:56.367
That same pressure will
be community because

00:12:56.367 --> 00:12:58.188
through our home and community
based services waivers

00:12:58.188 --> 00:13:00.504
that captures a great
deal of federal funding.

00:13:00.504 --> 00:13:03.403
They'll be out monitoring
to make sure we're meeting

00:13:03.403 --> 00:13:07.857
or complying with the home and
federal waiver requirements.

00:13:07.857 --> 00:13:11.932
And if by chance we're not
following those requirements,

00:13:11.932 --> 00:13:13.919
they will cut federal funding

00:13:13.919 --> 00:13:15.951
which is why there is a lot
pressure on regional centers

00:13:15.951 --> 00:13:18.143
and our service system to
capture those federal dollars

00:13:18.143 --> 00:13:21.643
and be in compliance with federal waivers.

00:13:27.647 --> 00:13:29.230
So who do we serve?

00:13:36.733 --> 00:13:39.890
As you can see, the Hispanic community

00:13:39.890 --> 00:13:43.890
and our white community
are the primary drivers.

00:13:51.997 --> 00:13:55.490
And when we look at who we
serve, we also have to be mindful

00:13:55.490 --> 00:13:58.240
of the unrepresented communities.

00:13:59.937 --> 00:14:02.489
One of the big things
that's talked about a lot

00:14:02.489 --> 00:14:04.863
at the legislature and
within the department

00:14:04.863 --> 00:14:06.492
and within the regional
centers now has to do

00:14:06.492 --> 00:14:10.659
with disparity in services
to different ethnic groups.

00:14:13.685 --> 00:14:16.664
A very interesting issue
that's come up with this

00:14:16.664 --> 00:14:20.877
and another slide will
show you has to do with,

00:14:20.877 --> 00:14:24.127
even though White is still the largest.

00:14:25.519 --> 00:14:27.039
They're starting to go down and Hispanic

00:14:27.039 --> 00:14:30.456
is starting to be a large area of growth.

00:14:31.443 --> 00:14:34.977
However when you look at
the utilization of services,

00:14:34.977 --> 00:14:38.477
you'll see that Hispanic is not utilizing

00:14:39.715 --> 00:14:41.616
a lot of services that
are available to them.

00:14:41.616 --> 00:14:45.783
We find this can be of
course the issue with culture

00:14:47.062 --> 00:14:49.846
but it is something
that we want to address.

00:14:49.846 --> 00:14:52.254
And it's something that the
legislature wants to address

00:14:52.254 --> 00:14:55.048
as there have also been
a lot complaints about,

00:14:55.048 --> 00:14:57.708
in different regions where the population

00:14:57.708 --> 00:14:59.818
in Hispanic or Black is high

00:14:59.818 --> 00:15:03.985
and yet utilization of
services seems to be unequal.

00:15:12.593 --> 00:15:15.016
So as you can see from this slide,

00:15:15.016 --> 00:15:17.433
even though Hispanic is high.

00:15:18.904 --> 00:15:23.071
They only utilize 79% of the
services that are authorized.

00:15:23.923 --> 00:15:25.724
Another interest thing that we found

00:15:25.724 --> 00:15:27.460
with the White population.

00:15:27.460 --> 00:15:30.664
They use 84% but they
also are the largest user

00:15:30.664 --> 00:15:34.414
of residential services
which is interesting.

00:15:40.326 --> 00:15:42.458
So what are some of the recent changes

00:15:42.458 --> 00:15:46.480
that have come about
at the department now?

00:15:46.480 --> 00:15:48.762
I'm sure many of you remember back in 2009

00:15:48.762 --> 00:15:50.599
when there were system wide reductions.

00:15:50.599 --> 00:15:53.901
How difficult it was to
get services for anybody.

00:15:53.901 --> 00:15:57.422
Now that the budget has
started to make a return

00:15:57.422 --> 00:16:00.303
and we've got a little
more funding to our system.

00:16:00.303 --> 00:16:04.470
We're able to as you can see
restore early start program.

00:16:07.033 --> 00:16:11.687
Restoration of prior services
provider payment reductions,

00:16:11.687 --> 00:16:13.801
rate increases for specific service types

00:16:13.801 --> 00:16:15.827
and to provide additional compensation

00:16:15.827 --> 00:16:18.635
for direct service providers.

00:16:18.635 --> 00:16:21.458
There's additional funding
for a paid internship program

00:16:21.458 --> 00:16:22.736
and service provider placement

00:16:22.736 --> 00:16:26.052
incentive funding for competitive
integrated employment.

00:16:26.052 --> 00:16:27.917
And I find this one to
be really interesting

00:16:27.917 --> 00:16:30.690
'cause when we did stakeholders meetings

00:16:30.690 --> 00:16:33.989
to talk about how to implement
this paid internship program.

00:16:33.989 --> 00:16:36.667
Legislature provided $10
million for this program

00:16:36.667 --> 00:16:38.496
and as I said earlier
that there was a point

00:16:38.496 --> 00:16:41.520
when we only got $20 million
for the entire system

00:16:41.520 --> 00:16:44.431
and we were able to get $10
million for this one program.

00:16:44.431 --> 00:16:46.348
We've come a long ways.

00:16:48.276 --> 00:16:50.159
And we have additional
funding to regional centers

00:16:50.159 --> 00:16:52.006
to address purchase
and service disparities

00:16:52.006 --> 00:16:54.442
for underserved populations.

00:16:54.442 --> 00:16:57.217
In fact we get $11 million
annually to address

00:16:57.217 --> 00:16:59.467
that issue I just talked about

00:16:59.467 --> 00:17:02.300
between the different ethnicities.

00:17:06.338 --> 00:17:07.508
We also received increased funding

00:17:07.508 --> 00:17:11.595
to address state wide
minimum wage increases.

00:17:11.595 --> 00:17:13.453
Increase funding to facilitate development

00:17:13.453 --> 00:17:15.939
of community resources for
individuals transitioning

00:17:15.939 --> 00:17:19.856
from DCs and to meet
challenging service needs.

00:17:23.843 --> 00:17:27.172
We have increased funding for
regional center operations

00:17:27.172 --> 00:17:29.512
including reducing case load ratios

00:17:29.512 --> 00:17:32.196
and new positions at regional centers.

00:17:32.196 --> 00:17:36.103
Some of those new positions
include a cultural specialist,

00:17:36.103 --> 00:17:38.105
an employment specialist

00:17:38.105 --> 00:17:40.826
and a federal program specialist too.

00:17:40.826 --> 00:17:43.180
To again ensure that regional
centers are able to comply

00:17:43.180 --> 00:17:47.347
with home and community
based service waiver issues.

00:17:48.533 --> 00:17:50.384
As I said those dollars are going to be

00:17:50.384 --> 00:17:52.301
critical to our system.

00:17:59.980 --> 00:18:03.902
And then new DDS
priorities and initiatives.

00:18:03.902 --> 00:18:06.186
Of course one of the reasons
Nancy is not here has to do

00:18:06.186 --> 00:18:08.591
with new legislation and funding

00:18:08.591 --> 00:18:12.935
so it's gonna be incumbent
upon us to operationalize

00:18:12.935 --> 00:18:17.294
and implement any new
legislation and funding.

00:18:17.294 --> 00:18:19.435
Home and community based settings.

00:18:19.435 --> 00:18:23.602
The federal rules are out
there for people to review.

00:18:25.684 --> 00:18:27.296
They're critical for our federal dollars

00:18:27.296 --> 00:18:30.479
and we need to be in compliance
with the federal home

00:18:30.479 --> 00:18:32.537
and community based settings rules.

00:18:32.537 --> 00:18:36.704
By March of 2019, we have
new community service models.

00:18:38.798 --> 00:18:40.716
Enhance behavior support homes.

00:18:40.716 --> 00:18:42.205
We have adult residential facilities

00:18:42.205 --> 00:18:44.804
for persons with special
health care needs.

00:18:44.804 --> 00:18:47.982
We have added delayed egress
secure perimeter services

00:18:47.982 --> 00:18:50.526
to our residential
programs that's available

00:18:50.526 --> 00:18:52.943
for folks to use when needed.

00:18:56.596 --> 00:18:58.521
One of the things I would
say about the enhance

00:18:58.521 --> 00:19:03.354
or what is also called the (ARFPSHN)

00:19:03.354 --> 00:19:05.033
or the Adult Residential
Facility for Persons

00:19:05.033 --> 00:19:06.974
with Special Healthcare Needs.

00:19:06.974 --> 00:19:09.753
They are starting to grow rapidly.

00:19:09.753 --> 00:19:14.536
They have proven to be a
very effective and successful

00:19:14.536 --> 00:19:18.171
service for people that
are medically fragile.

00:19:18.171 --> 00:19:21.133
In fact, hopefully one of the initiatives

00:19:21.133 --> 00:19:25.421
might be to spread that
program for children

00:19:25.421 --> 00:19:27.341
that are medically fragile.

00:19:27.341 --> 00:19:30.526
That's what we're looking at next.

00:19:30.526 --> 00:19:33.780
We already have, in past
I've talked about (ARFPSHN)

00:19:33.780 --> 00:19:38.157
program because it was modeled
after the special program

00:19:38.157 --> 00:19:42.110
for children which was
previously called Bates Homes.

00:19:42.110 --> 00:19:43.761
And the (ARFPSHN) was modeled after that

00:19:43.761 --> 00:19:45.177
but the problem with the Bates Homes

00:19:45.177 --> 00:19:46.322
is that they can only be done

00:19:46.322 --> 00:19:48.718
in small family homes or foster homes.

00:19:48.718 --> 00:19:50.511
We wanna expand that program

00:19:50.511 --> 00:19:52.127
so it can be done in a group home.

00:19:52.127 --> 00:19:53.853
So that it doesn't have to just be run

00:19:53.853 --> 00:19:56.603
by the person that owns the home.

00:19:58.893 --> 00:20:02.516
Then of course we have the
self-determine patient program

00:20:02.516 --> 00:20:03.702
and I don't know if people know.

00:20:03.702 --> 00:20:05.832
We've been trying to get this
self-determination program

00:20:05.832 --> 00:20:08.459
off the ground for quite some time.

00:20:08.459 --> 00:20:10.930
Actually we're the only
state that had to apply

00:20:10.930 --> 00:20:14.004
to the federal government for
the self-determination program

00:20:14.004 --> 00:20:15.343
and we send our application

00:20:15.343 --> 00:20:18.510
in way back in 2014, December of 2014.

00:20:19.883 --> 00:20:21.574
And we're still responding to questions

00:20:21.574 --> 00:20:25.147
from the federal government to try to get

00:20:25.147 --> 00:20:26.801
this thing off the ground.

00:20:26.801 --> 00:20:29.798
Even once we get it off the
ground it's still just suppose

00:20:29.798 --> 00:20:33.245
to be a three year pilot
and could serve 2500 people.

00:20:33.245 --> 00:20:36.320
But we feeling like we're
getting a lot closer

00:20:36.320 --> 00:20:38.356
to answering all their
questions and hopefully,

00:20:38.356 --> 00:20:42.523
we'll get this thing going
in a short period of time.

00:20:43.798 --> 00:20:45.832
One of the things about the
self-determination program

00:20:45.832 --> 00:20:47.291
that people may not notice that people

00:20:47.291 --> 00:20:50.347
get to direct their own budget.

00:20:50.347 --> 00:20:53.764
So depending on what their IPP needs are,

00:20:54.680 --> 00:20:57.539
they'll receive a budget to
carry out that on their own

00:20:57.539 --> 00:20:59.905
and they can choose
their service providers.

00:20:59.905 --> 00:21:01.164
Who they wanna get services from,

00:21:01.164 --> 00:21:04.497
who they want to get their support from.

00:21:05.642 --> 00:21:10.158
It should be a very interesting
program once it gets here.

00:21:10.158 --> 00:21:12.404
And then again, I wanna reduce inequities

00:21:12.404 --> 00:21:14.904
and disparities in our system.

00:21:17.499 --> 00:21:19.929
Reporting on regional centers,
I don't know if people

00:21:19.929 --> 00:21:21.117
have looked at our website lately

00:21:21.117 --> 00:21:24.039
but we have a dashboard on our website now

00:21:24.039 --> 00:21:25.873
where a lot of regional center data

00:21:25.873 --> 00:21:28.745
on individual regional
centers can be found.

00:21:28.745 --> 00:21:30.275
And so you can look at our website,

00:21:30.275 --> 00:21:33.873
you can look at the dashboard
for regional centers

00:21:33.873 --> 00:21:35.653
and get a lot of data on

00:21:35.653 --> 00:21:38.733
what that particular
regional center is doing.

00:21:38.733 --> 00:21:41.867
And of course the
developmental center closure

00:21:41.867 --> 00:21:43.128
and transition activities.

00:21:43.128 --> 00:21:45.543
There's a great deal of
work and activity going on

00:21:45.543 --> 00:21:47.515
to transition people appropriately

00:21:47.515 --> 00:21:49.623
from the developmental centers.

00:21:49.623 --> 00:21:52.382
One of the big complaints
during the Coffel years

00:21:52.382 --> 00:21:55.497
was that we moved people too fast.

00:21:55.497 --> 00:21:57.069
I can tell you that that's not the case

00:21:57.069 --> 00:21:58.640
with the developmental centers closures

00:21:58.640 --> 00:22:01.167
for Fairview, Porterville and Sonoma

00:22:01.167 --> 00:22:03.238
which are the three remaining
developmental centers.

00:22:03.238 --> 00:22:05.643
There is a lot of transition
activity that goes on

00:22:05.643 --> 00:22:07.447
with each individual that moves

00:22:07.447 --> 00:22:10.197
from those developmental centers.

00:22:11.513 --> 00:22:14.221
And regional centers are
doing a great deal of work

00:22:14.221 --> 00:22:16.560
to develop appropriate resources for folks

00:22:16.560 --> 00:22:18.598
and see that they are moved appropriately.

00:22:18.598 --> 00:22:21.253
And once they move the quality of services

00:22:21.253 --> 00:22:25.070
they provide is appropriate as well.

00:22:25.070 --> 00:22:28.181
And then we continue to
provide community development

00:22:28.181 --> 00:22:31.406
funds to regional centers
to develop resources.

00:22:31.406 --> 00:22:33.658
Not only for people coming
out of developmental centers

00:22:33.658 --> 00:22:37.658
but for people that are
in our college hospital,

00:22:38.545 --> 00:22:40.712
jails and we still have some consumers

00:22:40.712 --> 00:22:42.703
that live out of state
that we wanna bring back

00:22:42.703 --> 00:22:43.703
to California.

00:22:43.703 --> 00:22:45.910
'Cause we believe California
is the most appropriate

00:22:45.910 --> 00:22:48.561
and our system was developed
to serve people in California.

00:22:48.561 --> 00:22:50.363
So those folks that had
to be placed out of state

00:22:50.363 --> 00:22:52.270
for one reason or
another, regional centers

00:22:52.270 --> 00:22:53.985
are developing resources
so that they can bring

00:22:53.985 --> 00:22:55.985
them back to California.

