I didn't wanna do that one.

00:24:15.800 --> 00:24:17.802
Shelton was speaking because
I knew I would spill it

00:24:17.802 --> 00:24:21.219
and fall down and stuff so thanks so much

00:24:22.597 --> 00:24:25.169
for inviting us to speak today.

00:24:25.169 --> 00:24:27.788
I feel really honored.

00:24:27.788 --> 00:24:30.373
This conference has a great reputation

00:24:30.373 --> 00:24:34.123
and I know you guys will
have a great couple of days

00:24:34.123 --> 00:24:35.774
with all the sessions that are going on.

00:24:35.774 --> 00:24:39.941
So I will give you a brief,
short biography of me.

00:24:42.414 --> 00:24:45.824
I started in direct service in
1989 in a sheltered workshop

00:24:45.824 --> 00:24:47.371
with 110 people with intellectual

00:24:47.371 --> 00:24:49.355
and developmental disabilities,

00:24:49.355 --> 00:24:52.336
and we had about 20 folks
working in the community.

00:24:52.336 --> 00:24:56.226
And over 15 years, we shut
the sheltered workshop

00:24:56.226 --> 00:24:59.420
and got 110 people
working in the community.

00:24:59.420 --> 00:25:01.768
This was in Santa Cruz, California.

00:25:01.768 --> 00:25:06.042
It was outside of the closure
of Agnews Developmental Center

00:25:06.042 --> 00:25:09.342
and the part I was lucky to play there.

00:25:09.342 --> 00:25:10.449
The closure of the workshop

00:25:10.449 --> 00:25:11.651
and moving people in the community.

00:25:11.651 --> 00:25:15.739
Employment was certainly
one of the high water marks

00:25:15.739 --> 00:25:18.572
of the work I've been involved in.

00:25:20.178 --> 00:25:24.345
So after that I played a lot
of roles in an organization

00:25:27.424 --> 00:25:30.841
like many of the old timers in the system

00:25:32.924 --> 00:25:34.116
including Nancy Bargmann.

00:25:34.116 --> 00:25:37.765
I had a lot of different
roles that hopefully prepared

00:25:37.765 --> 00:25:40.167
me for the work we're doing now.

00:25:40.167 --> 00:25:43.876
I was involved in services
and supported employment

00:25:43.876 --> 00:25:46.178
and as I said and in supporting living

00:25:46.178 --> 00:25:47.551
and independent living

00:25:47.551 --> 00:25:50.796
and in children's rest bed
and just a broad variety

00:25:50.796 --> 00:25:52.987
of the provision of services

00:25:52.987 --> 00:25:57.099
and learned a lot from the
people we served in those years.

00:25:57.099 --> 00:26:00.116
And then I consulted for nine
years which was a shock to me.

00:26:00.116 --> 00:26:01.402
I thought I'd do it for a year

00:26:01.402 --> 00:26:03.581
but the work was just so interesting.

00:26:03.581 --> 00:26:06.252
A lot of it had to do
with the closure of Agnews

00:26:06.252 --> 00:26:10.173
Developmental Center in the
middle of those nine years.

00:26:10.173 --> 00:26:14.340
Certainly between 2004 and
2009 when Agnews closed

00:26:15.866 --> 00:26:20.033
and that included work to
help East Bay group found

00:26:21.055 --> 00:26:22.837
Algeria Community Living.

00:26:22.837 --> 00:26:26.089
Which is a wonderful
provider in the East Bay,

00:26:26.089 --> 00:26:29.049
all throughout the East Bay.

00:26:29.049 --> 00:26:33.216
Also I was director of the
quality management system

00:26:35.067 --> 00:26:37.528
for the Bay Area project which
was the closure of Agnews.

00:26:37.528 --> 00:26:41.334
Where got to see the
transformation of folks

00:26:41.334 --> 00:26:44.792
from living in an institution
to living in the community

00:26:44.792 --> 00:26:48.092
and I got to see 300 individual stories

00:26:48.092 --> 00:26:52.938
really of the stunning
changes in people's lives.

00:26:52.938 --> 00:26:56.306
People in their 60s
and 70s and 80s and 90s

00:26:56.306 --> 00:26:58.259
mostly moved out into the community

00:26:58.259 --> 00:26:59.709
and really got a new lease on life

00:26:59.709 --> 00:27:03.394
and got to do things extraordinary,

00:27:03.394 --> 00:27:06.311
sort of transformational things so.

00:27:07.236 --> 00:27:09.124
And then the last three years prior to me

00:27:09.124 --> 00:27:11.985
coming to Golden Gate nine months ago.

00:27:11.985 --> 00:27:15.658
I was the CEO of The Pomeroy Center

00:27:15.658 --> 00:27:16.786
used to be called the Rec Center

00:27:16.786 --> 00:27:18.795
for the handicapped or (RCH).

00:27:18.795 --> 00:27:22.398
A legacy 60 year old provider
in the Southwest corner

00:27:22.398 --> 00:27:26.565
of San Francisco that was
a leader in its history.

00:27:29.353 --> 00:27:31.922
Some decades around recreation and people

00:27:31.922 --> 00:27:34.582
with developmental disabilities

00:27:34.582 --> 00:27:36.139
and that was a great experience.

00:27:36.139 --> 00:27:39.543
So now I'm charged with
running one of these

00:27:39.543 --> 00:27:42.431
interestingly these
called regional centers.

00:27:42.431 --> 00:27:45.001
There's only 21 in the state.

00:27:45.001 --> 00:27:49.127
Shelton referenced that
we are 5O1c3 non profits

00:27:49.127 --> 00:27:52.685
and some of the greatest innovation

00:27:52.685 --> 00:27:54.516
from the highest highs and lowest lows

00:27:54.516 --> 00:27:55.678
have come from the fact that

00:27:55.678 --> 00:27:58.358
we are a non profit organization.

00:27:58.358 --> 00:28:00.387
Though we do much of
the work of government.

00:28:00.387 --> 00:28:04.304
We are not government
agencies, not yet anyway.

00:28:05.167 --> 00:28:08.725
So one thing that's very interesting is

00:28:08.725 --> 00:28:12.102
and I really never completely fact checked

00:28:12.102 --> 00:28:12.935
where this came from.

00:28:12.935 --> 00:28:14.645
But I believe that the
original design in the regional

00:28:14.645 --> 00:28:18.207
centers was to add a regional
center for every million

00:28:18.207 --> 00:28:21.432
in the general population in California.

00:28:21.432 --> 00:28:25.034
In which case today,
we'd 40 regional centers

00:28:25.034 --> 00:28:28.704
rather than the 21 and
then as Shelton mentioned.

00:28:28.704 --> 00:28:31.306
The other way to look at
that is just the intakes

00:28:31.306 --> 00:28:32.971
into the system.

00:28:32.971 --> 00:28:37.138
Each year about 13000,
14000 and that's the size of

00:28:38.085 --> 00:28:41.132
a medium sized regional center.

00:28:41.132 --> 00:28:44.048
So we are taking in about the equivalent

00:28:44.048 --> 00:28:46.996
of the people we serve in terms of

00:28:46.996 --> 00:28:49.241
adding a regional center each year.

00:28:49.241 --> 00:28:53.408
So I am going figure out
how to use these, forward.

