hands, I don't remember

00:44:28.829 --> 00:44:32.792
it was probably Tina
not Helen and she said,

00:44:32.792 --> 00:44:36.846
"Wait, why did you need
to have a court case

00:44:36.846 --> 00:44:38.750
"to enforce the law?

00:44:38.750 --> 00:44:40.787
"Why didn't people in your country

00:44:40.787 --> 00:44:43.052
"just follow the law
when you pass the law?

00:44:43.052 --> 00:44:45.817
(audience laughing)

00:44:45.817 --> 00:44:47.310
We all looked at each other
from the United States

00:44:47.310 --> 00:44:49.420
and went, you must not be from here.

00:44:49.420 --> 00:44:51.423
(audience laughing)

00:44:51.423 --> 00:44:55.892
This very northern European
thing that you pass a law so

00:44:55.892 --> 00:45:00.059
follow the law so that happened
with The Lanterman Act.

00:45:01.115 --> 00:45:04.302
I mean it was in place
and it was chugging along

00:45:04.302 --> 00:45:08.004
but it was really that 1985
states supreme court decision

00:45:08.004 --> 00:45:10.254
that said no, no it's true.

00:45:11.125 --> 00:45:13.202
You got to put your money
where your mouth is California.

00:45:13.202 --> 00:45:15.473
You got to find a system
and has to be based

00:45:15.473 --> 00:45:16.493
on individual needs,

00:45:16.493 --> 00:45:19.910
not categories of cookie cutter services.

00:45:21.816 --> 00:45:24.566
So now we get into the healthcare

00:45:26.397 --> 00:45:28.780
within a social justice frame.

00:45:28.780 --> 00:45:30.849
And I learn this mostly from my friends

00:45:30.849 --> 00:45:34.655
and colleagues and that USF program.

00:45:34.655 --> 00:45:37.238
In the disability rights movement

00:45:37.238 --> 00:45:39.655
sort of writ large the people

00:45:40.989 --> 00:45:43.577
with physical disabilities in particular

00:45:43.577 --> 00:45:46.581
were very uncomfortable
with the medical model.

00:45:46.581 --> 00:45:48.255
And I remember when we're closing Agnews,

00:45:48.255 --> 00:45:51.672
